  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka\u2019s petroleum sector trade unions to launch protest on Aug 22 against new reforms",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s Ceylon Petroleum Corporation trade unions will hold a protest on Monday (21) against the recent reforms made in the sector, Minister for Power and Energy said.",
        "\u201cCPC Trade unions affiliated with all political parties are to oppose the proposed reforms,\u201d Minister Kanchana Wijesekera said in a Tweet.",
        "He said he has met all the Unions and discussed the proposed reforms and their importance.",
        "However, the minister said the protest march against the proposed reforms will still occur tomorrow (August 22).",
        "\u201cCPC & CPC reforms are a must & will continue to work to implement them.\u201d",
        "Minister Wijesekara in early August said that there are multiple reasons for the CPC to operate under losses, with selling at subsidized rates, rupee depreciation, dues from government-owned institutes and overpaid, inefficient and bloated staffing being prominent reasons.",
        "CPC provides fuel for transport services in the country including, the Transportation Board, Railway Department, and Sri Lankan Airlines while also providing fuel for the Ceylon Electricity Board for thermal power generation.",
        "Dues from SriLankan airlines which values up to 300 million US dollars and 60 billion rupees from CEB is also contributing factor to the losses of CPC."
      ],
